<h1>Your Paradigm Match</h1>
<p class="subtitle">Based on your step-by-step thinking style</p>

<div class="match-card">
  <div class="match-score">‚≠ê Best Match</div>
  <div class="match-header">
    <div class="match-icon">üìã</div>
    <div>
      <div class="match-title">Imperative / Procedural</div>
      <div class="match-sub">Step-by-step, you're in control</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="match-desc">
    You think in <strong>ordered steps</strong> ‚Äî do this, then that, then check this condition. Procedural programming is exactly that: you write a sequence of instructions the computer executes top-to-bottom. It maps directly to how you naturally break problems apart. You're the director; the code is the script.
  </p>

  <div class="section-title">Why it fits you</div>
  <div class="traits">
    <span class="trait">‚úÖ You sequence naturally</span>
    <span class="trait">‚úÖ Clear cause-and-effect</span>
    <span class="trait">‚úÖ Easy to trace & debug</span>
    <span class="trait">‚úÖ Great for beginners</span>
    <span class="trait">‚úÖ Most languages support it</span>
  </div>

  <div class="section-title">Languages that feel natural</div>
  <div class="lang-pills">
    <span class="lang-pill">Python</span>
    <span class="lang-pill">C</span>
    <span class="lang-pill">JavaScript</span>
    <span class="lang-pill">Go</span>
    <span class="lang-pill">Bash</span>
  </div>

  <button class="code-toggle" onclick="toggleCode()">üëÅ See what this looks like in code</button>
  <div class="code-block" id="codeBlock"><span class="cm"># Python ‚Äî Procedural style</span>
<span class="cm"># Make a cup of tea, step by step</span>

<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">boil_water</span>():
    <span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="str">"Heating water to 100¬∞C..."</span>)
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="str">"boiled water"</span>

<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">steep_tea</span>(water, minutes):
    <span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="str">f"Steeping tea for {minutes} minutes..."</span>)
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="str">"brewed tea"</span>

<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">make_tea</span>():
    water  = <span class="fn">boil_water</span>()       <span class="cm"># Step 1</span>
    tea    = <span class="fn">steep_tea</span>(water, <span class="num">3</span>) <span class="cm"># Step 2</span>
    <span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="str">"Tea is ready! ‚òï"</span>)    <span class="cm"># Step 3</span>

<span class="fn">make_tea</span>()
</div>

  <div class="tip-box">
    üí° <strong>Tip for you:</strong> Since you're neutral on "state & change," try Python first ‚Äî it lets you stay procedural but gently introduces you to other paradigms as you grow. You won't hit a wall.
  </div>
</div>

<h2>Other paradigms ‚Äî click to explore</h2>
<div class="others-grid">
  <div class="other-card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('expanded')">
    <div class="other-icon">üß©</div>
    <div class="other-header">
      <span class="other-name">Object-Oriented</span>
      <span class="other-fit fit-med">Medium fit</span>
    </div>
    <div class="other-desc">You model the world as objects with properties and behaviors. Great for large apps. May feel abstract at first if you're very step-oriented. Languages: Java, Python, C#, Ruby.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="other-card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('expanded')">
    <div class="other-icon">üî¢</div>
    <div class="other-header">
      <span class="other-name">Functional</span>
      <span class="other-fit fit-med">Medium fit</span>
    </div>
    <div class="other-desc">You describe transformations of data ‚Äî no steps, no mutation. Elegant and powerful, but a mindset shift from step-by-step. Languages: Haskell, Clojure, Elm, Scala.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="other-card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('expanded')">
    <div class="other-icon">üó£Ô∏è</div>
    <div class="other-header">
      <span class="other-name">Declarative</span>
      <span class="other-fit fit-low">Low fit (for now)</span>
    </div>
    <div class="other-desc">You say *what* you want, not how to get it. SQL and HTML are declarative. Hard to start here ‚Äî works best once you understand the "how" underneath.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="other-card" onclick="this.classList.toggle('expanded')">
    <div class="other-icon">‚ö°</div>
    <div class="other-header">
      <span class="other-name">Event-Driven</span>
      <span class="other-fit fit-med">Medium fit</span>
    </div>
    <div class="other-desc">Code reacts to events (clicks, messages, timers). Used heavily in UI and game dev. Pairs well with procedural thinking. Languages: JavaScript, C#, Swift.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
function toggleCode() {
  const block = document.getElementById('codeBlock');
  const btn = document.querySelector('.code-toggle');
  block.classList.toggle('visible');
  btn.textContent = block.classList.contains('visible') ? 'üôà Hide code' : 'üëÅ See what this looks like in code';
}
</script>
